GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 2



Overview of the Hypothetical Rexx Program The concept is an ISPF
application  presumably to be developed that would provide an advanced
X.509 certificate display on z/OS.  The application might be an
enhancement to RACFADM or might be a new application.  For convenience
in this paper I will refer to the ISPF application as RACFADM.

In addition we might make GETCERTS available to the z/OS community as a
standalone CBT application. Users could develop their own certificate
reports or other applications as they chose.

In the following discussion I will reference the sample Rexx EXEC,
TGETCERT. It is found in CHARLES.ALPHA.EXEC(TGETCERT).

The envisioned ISPF application, or RACFADM, would start by installing
GETCERTS as a Rexx environment. That process, and the basic calls to
GETCERTS using Rexx ADDRESS, are documented below under Loading and
Calling GETCERTS, and illustrated in the sample Rexx script, TGETCERT,
RACFADM would start by calling the CERTSUMM function, which is a
prerequisite to any other functions.

RACFADM would start by displaying a panel modeled after the SDSF job
displays.  Each detail line of the display would represent one
certificate. The user could scroll up and down, and/or left and right.
The fields to be displayed would be chosen at the discretion of the
developer, selected from the fields listed below under CERTSUMM. Some of
the fields may be as wide as 67 characters, so RACFADM would probably
truncate them and/or allow user-variable column widths similar to what
SDSF does. The display of some fields might be deferred, at the
discretion of the implementer, to any Certificate Detail request.

A primary command would let the user alternatively display keyrings, one
per detail line. To obtain the data for the display, RACFADM would call
the RINGSUMM function. RINGSUMM returns only three Rexx stem variables,
so the panel design would be somewhat simpler (although one of the
fields, the keyring name, may be up to 237 characters wide, and may
contain special characters).

An important concept is certificate and keyring index numbers. An index
number is an integer, starting with 1, that is used as the tail of the
various compound variables for the certificate or keyring. The index
number is also used by GETCERTS to identify other certificates or
keyrings, such as in the CONCERT# keyring variable, which lists the
index numbers of the certificates connected to the ring, separated by
blanks.  Thus WORDS(CONCERT#.tail) would give the number of certificates
connected to

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 3



the keyring with a keyring index of tail, and WORD( CONCERT#.tail, 1)
would be the index number of the first certificate connected to the
keyring. The sample Rexx script TGETCERT illustrates this logic. (All
GETCERT returned variables with stem names ending in # are similar lists
of index numbers.)

It is envisioned that the certificate and keyring primary displays would
support various line commands similar to the SDSF S line command
(subject to the discretion of the RACFADM author). The anticipated
commands, and a brief summary of how they might be implemented, are
listed below.

Certificate Line Command Functions:

    List Detail. This would be implemented by performing the CERTDETL
function, passing the index number of the certificate. I will leave it
to the discretion of the implementor how to display the various returned
data, including any data deferred from the primary certificate display.

    List Chain. This would be implemented by following the certificate
chain in ISSUER# for each certificate. Note that a certificate could
have multiple issuers. It is unlikely, but it is possible.1 There is an
example of how a List Chain would work in the sample Rexx EXEC,
TGETCERT.

    List Dependents. This is the reverse of List Chain and is
implemented by displaying the certificates listed in the certificates
LEAF#. The sample script, TGETCERT, has examples.

    List Connected Keyrings. This function would require that a
RINGSUMM function had been called. The list of connected keyrings is
found in KEYRING#.

Keyring Line Command Functions

    List Connected Certificate Detail. This function would be
implemented by calling the RINGCONN function and displaying the returned
data.


1
https://scotthelme.co.uk/cross-signing-alternate-trust-paths-how-they-
      work/
