GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 4



Loading and Calling GETCERTS
GETCERTS is invoked by a Rexx program as a Rexx ADDRESS environment.
RACFADM would install GETCERTS as a Rexx environment using the separate
program EZSUBCOM.

EZSUBCOM must be available to the Rexx program. It may reside in
ISPLLIB.  GETCERTS must reside in the MVS content management chain
(STEPLIB, etc.).  ISPLLIB is not searched for GETCERTS. EZSUBCOM is
separately documented but the following is an overview of using EZSUBCOM
to install GETCERTS as a Rexx environment.

EZSUBCOM must be invoked with Rexx CALL; it cannot be invoked with ISPF
SELECT PGM.

Initialization
ADDRESS ISPEXEC "LIBDEF ISPLLIB DATASET ID(ezsubcom.loadlib) STACK"
ADDRESS TSO "ALLOC FI(loadlbdd) DA(getcerts.loadlib) SHR"
ADDRESS TSO 'ALLOC FI(GCPRINT) desired alloc operands'
Call 'EZSUBCOM' 'ADDLESUB', 'GETCERTS', , , 'loadlibdd'

GCPRINT may be allocated to the terminal, to DUMMY or to a dataset as
the RACFADM author prefers. It must be allocated before the call to
EZSUBCOM ADDLESUB. If GETCERTS cannot open GCPRINT then the ADDLESUB
call will fail.  GETCERTS opens GCPRINT RECFM=VBA, LRECL=133.

Rexx will load EZSUBCOM from ISPLLIB but not GETCERTS. If GETCERTS is
not in the STEPLIB chain then you must allocate a DD to the appropriate
load library and pass it as a parameter to EZSUBCOM as shown above.

CALL EZSUBCOM returns its result in the Rexx special variable RESULT.
RESULT is a string consisting of a  return code 0, 4, 8, 12 or 16
following the usual MVS conventions and, if the return code is non-zero,
a string describing the error or warning condition. Sample Rexx code:

Retvalue = RESULT
Parse var Retvalue retcode errmsg
If retcode <> 0 Then Do
  Say 'EZSUBCOM' retcode errmsg
  If retcode > 4 Then /* Deal with error */
  End

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 5



Information Retrieval
See Certificate and Ring Information Retrieval below.

Termination
CALL 'EZSUBCOM' 'DELETE', 'GETCERTS'
ADDRESS TSO 'FREE FI(GCPRINT)'
ADDRESS TSO 'FREE FI(loadlbdd)'

See Initialization above for EZSUBCOM return result information.

Certificate and Ring Information Retrieval

Linkage
ADDRESS GETCERTS function parameters

The various functions and parameters are documented in detail below.

ADDRESS is limited to returning a single value, the Rexx special
variable RC. If the CEEPIPI call returns a non-zero value (which in our
experience is unlikely) then EZSUBCOM returns the CEEPIPI return code;
otherwise EZSUBCOM returns the return code from the module. CEEPIPI
subroutine invocation return codes are documented here:
https://www.ibm.com/docs/en/zos/3.2.0?topic=csis-return- codes . All of
the non-zero values are should-not-occur conditions.

GETCERTS logs all error and warning conditions to the GCPRINT data set.
In a future enhancement GETCERTS will return error and warning
conditions that it detects in Rexx variables. GETCERTS returns :

    0  Successful function, no error or warning conditions detected
    4  One or more warning conditions detected.
    8  One or more error conditions detected in the RACF certificate
       store.
    12 One or more error conditions detected in the parameters passed
       on ADDRESS or in executing them.
    16  Fatal error condition in GETCERTS. GETCERTS could not continue.

Returned Information
Certificate and keyring data is returned to RACFADM in Rexx variables.
RACFADM may specify name prefixes  a character string to be prepended to
the defined variable names.

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 6



Data Formats Date and Time Format. Dates and times are returned in ISO
8601 (2026-02- 21T11:46:33): its a standard, its sortable, its
unambiguous for international customers, and its easy to truncate to 10
characters if time is not needed.

Hexadecimal Format. Unpunctuated uppercase hex is common on the
mainframe:  08C6A634815E296535A4¦ Uppercase hex with colon as a byte
separator is used by RACF: 7A:2B:6A:F3:C4:91:DF:D3... in some places and
unpunctuated lowercase hex in others. Lowercase hex with colon as a byte
separator is used by OpenSSL:  08:c6:a6:34:81:5e:29:65:21:35:a4¦
Gskkyman uses uppercase hex with blank as a byte separator in some
places and unpunctuated lowercase hex in others.  GETCERTS follows RACFs
lead and uses 7A:2B:6A:F3:C4:91:DF:D3... but I am open to suggestions.

True/False Format. TRUE and FALSE are returned as 1 and 0 for convenient
usage from Rexx. RACFADM might choose to display the values as
TRUE/FALSE, YES/NO, TRUST/NOTRUST or otherwise.

GETCERTS Functions
RACFADM will call the CERTSUMM (Get Certificate Summary) and RINGSUMM
(Get Ring Summary) functions once and display summary information. Then,
if the user asks for detail for a particular certificate, RACFADM will
call CERTDETL (Get Certificate Detail) for that certificate. Or if a
user asks for the connected certificates for a particular keyring then
RACFADM would call RINGCONN (Get Keyring Connected Certificates).

If the user wished to refresh the certificate or ring data it should be
possible to call the CERTSUMM and/or RINGSUMM functions again, but this
has not been tested.

Summary information is returned in a set of Rexx compound variables with
a defined stem name and a numerical tail.

For example, assuming a certificate variable prefix of C_, the label
information for the certificates will be returned in C_LABEL.1,
C_LABEL.2, C_LABEL.3 and so forth, with a count of certificates in
C_LABEL.0. Similarly, the not after date for the certificates will be
returned in C_NOTAFTER.1, C_NOTAFTER.2, C_NOTAFTER.3, and so forth.

In this paper I will refer to the Rexx stem variable tail value (1, 2
and 3 in the examples above) as the certificates or keyrings index
number.

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 7



The detail information would similarly be returned in a set of Rexx
variables, but the detail variables would for the most part be simple
Rexx variables. The certificate detail data would apply to only the one
certificate so there would be no need for compound qualification. The
exception would be several pieces of detail information that might
repeat a variable number of times. That information would be returned in
compound variables using the usual .1, .2, .3 and .0 convention.

Why not simply return all of the certificates or keyrings data in the
summary variables? Two reasons:

1. The data is potentially voluminous. The subject and issuer names may
be up to 2048 characters each. One of our RACFADM users has over 2000
certificates. Thats a lot of data.

2. Some of the detail data repeats in stem variables with numeric tails.
As the summary data already repeats in stem variables with numeric
tails, that would imply double numeric tails        variables like
C_SAN.37.3 for the third SAN (Subject Alternate Name) for certificate
number 37. I feel that would be confusing.

Why a separate RINGINFO call? Because ring retrieval requires additional
permissions beyond those required for certificate retrieval, and some
users might not have those permissions and would prefer not to get
security violations.

Detail Description of GETCERTS Functions

Common Parameters
These parameters may be specified with any of the functions.

PREFIX prefix specifies an optional prefix to be prepended to the
returned Rexx variable names. For example, assuming a certificate
variable prefix of C_, the label information for the certificates will
be returned in C_LABEL.1, C_LABEL.2, C_LABEL.3 and so forth, with a
count of certificates in C_LABEL.0. The prefix may be any length but
prefixes longer than four characters may have a slight negative effect
on performance.

VERBOSE specifies that additional informational messages are to be
output to GCPRINT by GETCERTS. The VERBOSE output is potentially
voluminous.

CERTSUMM  Get Certificate Summary
CERTSUMM retrieves certificate summary information for all certificates.

ADDRESS GETCERTS CERTSUMM [PREFIX prefix] [VERBOSE]

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 8



CERTSUMM is required as the first parameter. It specifies the
certificate summary function.

See also Common Parameters above.

The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any order.

The CERTSUMM function requires the following RACF permissions:

    READ authority to IRR.RADMIN.RLIST (or IRR.RADMIN.*) in the FACILITY
    class.  READ authority to CSFOWH in the CSFSERV class; or
    CSF.CSFSERV.AUTH.CSFOWH.DISABLE resource profile defined in the
    XFACILIT class.

And either

If the *.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST profile or any
userid.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST profile exists in the RDATALIB class,
then READ authority to the *.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST profile.

    Otherwise UPDATE authority to IRR.DIGTCERT.LISTRING in the FACILITY
    class.

Rexx variables set by CERTSUMM are listed in the table below. The Rexx
stem names are prefixed as described above. RACFADM might choose to
defer some of these fields to any detail display.


Rexx Stem  Description Notes

CERTDADD
Date certificate added to RACF. See Date and Time Format above.

CERTUADD
RACF ID of user who actually added certificate to RACF. Not
necessarily the same as the certificate's CERTUSER.

AUTHKID
Authority Key Identifier. See Hexadecimal Format above.

CAUSAGE
From basic constraints. 1 if CA:TRUE; 0 if CA: FALSE

CERTUSER
Certificate owner. 1 to 8 characters. CERTAUTH and SITE
returned as irrcerta and irrsitec (lower case) respectively.

FINGERPR
SHA-256 fingerprint of the certificate.  32 bytes, reported as
95 characters, as of the certificate reported by RACF. See Hexadecimal
Format above.

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 9



Rexx Stem  Description Notes

ISSUER#
Index number(s) of issuer certificates. Normally at most one
issuer, but because of cross-signing, expired intermediates and other
somewhat unusual circumstances a certificate may have multiple issuers.
(See footnotes under Overview of the Hypothetical Rexx Program.)
Multiple Issuer index numbers are separated by blanks. Empty string if
no issuer certificate present. Empty string for self-signed
certificates.

ISSUER$
Short issuer name.  Issuer name shortened to most significant
RDN by algorithm. Up to 67 characters, but RACFADM may display less if
so chooses.

KEYALGO
Public key algorithm. Name such as rsaEncryption.

KEYLEN
Public key length in bits.

LABEL
Certificate label 1 to 32 characters. May include embedded special
characters, including blanks and quotes. Quotes are not doubled by
GETCERTS.

LEAF#
Index numbers of Empty string if none. Multiple index certificates
signed numbers separated by blanks. Self not by this certificate
included for self-signed certificates.

NOTAFTER
Certificate expiration date and time.  See Date and Time Format
above.

NOTBEFOR
Certificate start date and time.  See Date and Time Format
above.

PRIVKEY
Is there a private 1 if private key in RACF, 0 if not. (Note 2)

SELFSIGN
Certificate is self- 1 if self-signed; 0 if not signed

SERIAL
Certificate serial number. See Hexadecimal Format above.

Note 2:  Meaningful only if certain RACF facilities are permitted;
otherwise will return 0.  See Usage note 4 in
https://www.ibm.com/docs/en/zos/3.2.0?topic=library-usage-notes



GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 10



Rexx Stem  Description Notes

SIGALGO
Signature algorithm A name like sha256WithRSAEncryption

SUBJECT$
Short subject name.  Subject name shortened to most significant
RDN by algorithm. Up to 67 characters, but RACFADM may display less if
so chooses.

SUBJKID
Subject Key Identifier. See Hexadecimal Format above.

THUMBPR
SHA-1 Thumbprint 20 bytes, formatted as 39 characters (used by
Windows). See Hexadecimal Format above.

TRUST
Certificate trust status. 1 if trusted; 0 if not status



RINGSUMM  Get Keyring Summary

RINGSUMM retrieves keyring summary information below for all rings and
certificate ring connections. May not precede the CERTSUMM call.

ADDRESS GETCERTS RINGSUMM [PREFIX prefix] [VERBOSE]

RINGSUMM is required as the first parameter. It specifies the keyring
summary function.

See also Common Parameters above.

The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any order.

RINGSUMM requires the following additional RACF permissions:

    UPDATE authority to IRR.DIGTCERT.LISTRING in the FACILITY class.  If
    any keyring profiles exist in the RDATALIB class, then READ
    authority to *.*.LST in RDATALIB.

Rexx variables set by RINGSUMM are listed in the tables below. RACFADM
might choose to defer displaying some of these fields to any certificate
detail function.

Additional certificate variables, indexed by certificate index number:

Rexx Stem  Description Notes
KEYRING#
Keyring index Integers separated by blanks. Empty numbers of
string if none or if Get Ring Summary connected keyrings has not been
called. Sorted into ascending keyring index sequence.


GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 11



Keyring variables, indexed by a keyring index number as a tail; for
example, RINGUSER.9. The .0 tails contain a count of elements.

Rexx Stem  Description Notes
CONCERT#
Certificate index Zero or more integers separated by blanks,
numbers of sorted into ascending sequence. An empty connected string if
no connected certificates. RACFADM certificates. may access the userid,
label and so forth of the certificates as desired using the returned
certificate index number and the appropriate Rexx variables.

NAME
Keyring name 1 to 237 characters. May contain lowercase
and special characters.

RINGUSER
Keyring owner 1 to 8 characters. Never irrcerta or irrsitec.


CERTDETL  Get Certificate Detail
CERTDETL retrieves certificate detail information for one certificate,
specified by certificate index number. The function may be called
multiple times to retrieve information for multiple certificates.

ADDRESS GETCERTS CERTDETL CERTINDX index [PREFIX prefix] [VERBOSE]


CERTDETL is required as the first parameter. It specifies the
certificate detail function.

CERTINDX index is required and specifies the certificate index number of
the certificate for which detail information is to be returned.

See also Common Parameters above.

The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any order.

The detail information variables ISSUER and SUBJECT are not compound
variables.  The remaining certificate detail variables are stem
variables following the usual Rexx convention. Assuming no change in
prefix, each call to the CEERTDETL function overwrites the variables
from the previous call.

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 12



Rexx Description Notes

EXTUSAGE
Extended key usage Stem variable. May be multiple usages.

ISSUER
Full issuer name May be up to 2048 characters

KEYUSAGE
Key usage Stem variable. May be multiple usages.  Character
strings like HANDSHAKE, DATAENCRYPT, DOCSIGN or CERTSIG.

SAN
Subject Alternative Stem variable; may be dozens or more. Format
Names DNS: www.foobar.com

SUBJECT
Full subject name May be up to 2048 characters


RINGCONN  Get Keyring Connected Certificates
RINGCONN retrieves a list of connected certificates and their attributes
for one keyring, specified by keyring index number. The function may be
called multiple times to retrieve information for multiple keyrings.

ADDRESS GETCERTS RINGCONN RINGINDX index [PREFIX prefix] [VERBOSE]


RINGCONN is required as the first parameter. It specifies the ring
connections function.

RINGINDX index is required and specifies the keyring index number of the
keyring for which connection information is to be returned.

See also Common Parameters above.

The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any order.

RINGCONN requires the following RACF permissions:

    READ authority to <virtual ring owner>.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST in
    the FACILITY class.

A list of connected certificates and their attributes are  returned as
Rexx compound variables with a numeric tail, following the usual
conventions. Each tail number represents the attributes of one connected
certificate. A keyring may have no connected certificates, in which case
all of the listed Rexx Stems will have a tail .0 with a value of 0.
Assuming no change in prefix, each call to the RINGCONN function
overwrites the variables from the previous call.

GETCERTS  RACFADM Certificate Library Module Page 13



Rexx Stem  Description Notes
CERTIF#
Certificate index RACFADM may access the userid, label and so
number  forth of the certificate as desired using the returned
certificate index number and the appropriate Rexx variables.

DEFAULT
Whether certificate 1 = default; 0 = not the default. Note that
a is the default on the keyring has at most one, and may have no keyring
default certificate.

USAGE
Certificate usage on may be CERTAUTH, PERSONAL, SITE or NONE.

